        <h1 class="heading-large govuk-!-margin-top-2">
            Have the PDFs been notarised and digitally signed by a notary?
        </h1>
        <p>
            To use the e-Apostille service, the documents must be uploaded as PDFs that have been notarised and
            digitally signed by
            a practicing notary public or solicitor.
        </p>

        <details class="govuk-details" data-module="govuk-details">
            <summary class="govuk-details__summary">
                <span class="govuk-details__summary-text">
                    How to prepare the PDF
                </span>
            </summary>
            <div class="govuk-details__text">
                <p class="govuk-body">
                    When the notary public or solicitor certifies the PDF, they must:
                </p>
                <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
                    <li>hold a valid UK practising certificate for the date the PDF is certified</li>
                    <li>sign with a digital signature registered with their name as listed by the relevant regulatory
                        body, for
                        example, The Law Society, Faculty Office</li>
                    <li>sign in the UK in the jurisdiction they are registered</li>
                    <li>use their personal digital signature, not a company signature (it must be valid on the day the
                        PDF is
                        certified)</li>
                    <li>include an image of their seal, if applicable, which must be on the same page of the document as
                        their
                        digital signature</li>
                    <li>include their name and company address</li>
                    <li>include the full date of certification, specifying the day, month and year (the certification
                        cannot be
                        post-dated)</li>
                    <li>state the action they have taken, for example, certified the document as a copy or witnessed a
                        signature
                    </li>
                    <li>make sure the certification is appropriate for the document type, for example, if the document
                        is a
                        scanned copy, it should be certified as a true copy of the original.</li>
                </ul>
                <p></p>
                <p class="govuk-body">
                    If the notary public or solicitor includes a cover sheet in the PDF,
                    it must make specific reference to all the documents within the PDF.
                    Make sure the cover sheet appears first in the PDF.
                </p>
                <p class="govuk-body">
                    Information on digitally signing a PDF may be found in the following sites:
                </p>
                <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
                    <li>in England and Wales by <a
                            href="https://www.thenotariessociety.org.uk/">The Notaries Society</a></li>
                    <li>in Scotland by the <a
                            href="https://www.lawscot.org.uk/">Law Society of Scotland</a></li>
                    <li>in Northern Ireland by the <a
                            href="https://www.lawsoc-ni.org/">Law Society of Northern Ireland</a></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </details>

